{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491464"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:47:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:47:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"946"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/946"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.14,0.46,0.04,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"946"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102127"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/946"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"946"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84584"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"351"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"9235"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1167"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1378"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12934"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18656"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35533"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102127"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of retrosternal burning chest pain, which is worse on bending forward. Each episode lasts for about an hour and is relieved with liquid antacid preparations. He finds the episodes occur after he has had dinner and is laying on the couch. He gets about five episodes a week currently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications besides the over-the-counter antacids, which partially control his symptoms. He smokes 20 cigarettes a day and has done so since the age of 25. He drinks a six-pack of beer most days. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His BMI is 35 kg/m2.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management for this man?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Advice to cease smoking","Gastric endoscopy","Pantoprazole","pH and manometric studies","Barium swallow"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe history is consistent with a diagnosis of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD). In a primary care setting where there are no red flags (e.g., weight loss, early satiety, family history of gastric cancers, fatigue, melaena, haematemesis, dysphagia), the history and response to a trial of a proton pump inhibitor (PPI), such as \u003Cstrong\u003Epantoprazole\u003C/strong\u003E, can be used to form the diagnosis and to provide rapid symptomatic relief. Further diagnostic studies such as \u003Cstrong\u003EpH and manometric studies\u003C/strong\u003E may be conducted if he fails to respond to management, but are not required at this stage. A \u003Cstrong\u003Ebarium swallow\u003C/strong\u003E is similarly not required due to the clear history for GORD. In the presence of any red flag symptoms, further investigation would be appropriate, either endoscopy or a barium study.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, arrangements should be made for a review in a couple of months time and if his symptoms persist, then an endoscopy could be considered. Additionally, endoscopy is often limited to assist the diagnosis of GORD as the majority of patients will not have visible lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Ecessation of smoking\u003C/strong\u003E may be to the overall advantage of the patient in terms of his general health and may improve his symptoms, getting him to stop smoking is unlikely to have much immediate impact and this man requires symptom relief using an acid-suppressing agent. His obesity is undoubtedly contributing towards his reflux and he also needs counselling on this aspect of his health. Reducing alcohol intake would likewise be beneficial to his overall health and may improve his GORD symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApart from red flag symptoms, an endoscopy should be considered in this patient when he reaches the age of 50. This would be undertaken to rule out undiagnosed Barrett\u0027s oesophagus. This is a cost-effective screening procedure in a 50-year-old man with GORD.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["GORD can be diagnosed on clinical grounds based on history and a good response to PPI medication.","Lifestyle modifications, including weight loss, smoking cessation, and alcohol reduction, are adjuncts to medical management of GORD."],"references":["Hill, 2021. Managing gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD) in adults: an update [online]. Access at: https://bpac.org.nz/bpj/2014/june/gord.aspx.","Kirby, Piterman, Nelson, Dent, 2008. Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease [online]. RACGP. Access at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afpbackissues/2008/200801/200801kirby.pdf.","Clinical practice guidelines for the diagnosis and management of Barrett\u2019s Oesophagus and Early Oesophageal Adenocarcinoma. https://wiki.cancer.org.au/australia/Guidelines:Barrett%27s","Katz, P. O., Dunbar, K. B., Schnoll-Sussman, F. H., Greer, K. B., Yadlapati, R., \u0026 Spechler, S. J. (2022). ACG Clinical Guideline for the Diagnosis and Management of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease. The American journal of gastroenterology, 117(1), 27\u201356. https://doi.org/10.14309/ajg.0000000000001538"]},"relationships"